aa(lp159
VStill, technology isn't the only thing pushing athletes forward.
p160
aVWhile indeed we haven't evolved
p161
aVinto a new species in a century,
p162
aVthe gene pool within competitive sports
p163
aVmost certainly has changed.
p164
aVIn the early half of the 20th century,
p165
aVphysical education instructors and coaches
p166
aVhad the idea that the average body type
p167
aVwas the best for all athletic endeavors:
p168
aVmedium height, medium weight, no matter the sport.
p169
aVAnd this showed in athletes' bodies.
p170
aVIn the 1920s, the average elite high-jumper
p171
aVand average elite shot-putter were the same exact size.
p172
aVBut as that idea started to fade away,
p173
aVas sports scientists and coaches realized that
p174
aVrather than the average body type,
p175
aVyou want highly specialized bodies
p176
aVthat fit into certain athletic niches,
p177
aVa form of artificial selection took place,
p178
aVa self-sorting for bodies that fit certain sports,
p179
aVand athletes' bodies became more different from one another.
p180
aVToday, rather than the same size as the average elite high jumper,
p181
aVthe average elite shot-putter
p182
aVis two and a half inches taller
p183
aVand 130 pounds heavier.
p184
aVAnd this happened throughout the sports world.
p185
aa(lp186
VIn fact, if you plot on a height versus mass graph
p187
aVone data point for each of two dozen sports
p188
aVin the first half of the 20th century, it looks like this.
p189
aVThere's some dispersal,
p190
aVbut it's kind of grouped around that average body type.
p191
aVThen that idea started to go away,
p192
aVand at the same time, digital technology \u2014
p193
aVfirst radio, then television and the Internet \u2014
p194
aVgave millions, or in some cases billions, of people
p195
aVa ticket to consume elite sports performance.
p196
aVThe financial incentives and fame and glory afforded elite athletes skyrocketed,
p197
aVand it tipped toward the tiny upper echelon of performance.
p198
aVIt accelerated the artificial selection for specialized bodies.
p199
aVAnd if you plot a data point for these same
p200
aVtwo dozen sports today, it looks like this.
p201
aVThe athletes' bodies have gotten
p202
aVmuch more different from one another.
p203
aVAnd because this chart looks like the charts
p204
aVthat show the expanding universe,
p205
aVwith the galaxies flying away from one another,
p206
aVthe scientists who discovered it call it
p207
aV"The Big Bang of Body Types."
p208
aa(lp209
VIn sports where height is prized, like basketball,
p210
aVthe tall athletes got taller.
p211
aVIn 1983, the National Basketball Association
p212
aVsigned a groundbreaking agreement
p213
aVmaking players partners in the league,
p214
aVentitled to shares of ticket revenues
p215
aVand television contracts.
p216
aVSuddenly, anybody who could be an NBA player
p217
aVwanted to be,
p218
aVand teams started scouring the globe
p219
aVfor the bodies that could help them win championships.
p220
aVAlmost overnight,
p221
aVthe proportion of men in the NBA
p222
aVwho are at least seven feet tall doubled
p223
aVto 10 percent.
p224
aVToday, one in 10 men in the NBA
p225
aVis at least seven feet tall,
p226
aVbut a seven-foot-tall man is incredibly rare
p227
aVin the general population \u2014
p228
aVso rare that if you know an American man
p229
aVbetween the ages of 20 and 40
p230
aVwho is at least seven feet tall,
p231
aVthere's a 17 percent chance
p232
aVhe's in the NBA right now.
p233
aV(Laughter)
p234
aVThat is, find six honest seven footers,
p235
aVone is in the NBA right now.
p236
aVAnd that's not the only way that NBA players' bodies are unique.
p237
aVThis is Leonardo da Vinci's "Vitruvian Man,"
p238
aVthe ideal proportions,
p239
aVwith arm span equal to height.
p240
aVMy arm span is exactly equal to my height.
p241
aVYours is probably very nearly so.
p242
aVBut not the average NBA player.
p243
aVThe average NBA player is a shade under 6'7",
p244
aVwith arms that are seven feet long.
p245
aVNot only are NBA players ridiculously tall,
p246
aVthey are ludicrously long.
p247
aVHad Leonardo wanted to draw
p248
aVthe Vitruvian NBA Player,
p249
aVhe would have needed a rectangle and an ellipse,
p250
aVnot a circle and a square.
