aa(lp252
VSo in sports where large size is prized,
p253
aVthe large athletes have gotten larger.
p254
aVConversely, in sports where diminutive stature is an advantage,
p255
aVthe small athletes got smaller.
p256
aVThe average elite female gymnast
p257
aVshrunk from 5'3" to 4'9" on average
p258
aVover the last 30 years,
p259
aVall the better for their power-to-weight ratio
p260
aVand for spinning in the air.
p261
aVAnd while the large got larger
p262
aVand the small got smaller,
p263
aVthe weird got weirder.
p264
aVThe average length of the forearm
p265
aVof a water polo player in relation
p266
aVto their total arm got longer,
p267
aVall the better for a forceful throwing whip.
p268
aVAnd as the large got larger,
p269
aVsmall got smaller, and the weird weirder.
p270
aVIn swimming, the ideal body type
p271
aVis a long torso and short legs.
p272
aVIt's like the long hull of a canoe
p273
aVfor speed over the water.
p274
aVAnd the opposite is advantageous in running.
p275
aVYou want long legs and a short torso.
p276
aVAnd this shows in athletes' bodies today.
p277
aVHere you see Michael Phelps,
p278
aVthe greatest swimmer in history,
p279
aVstanding next to Hicham El Guerrouj,
p280
aVthe world record holder in the mile.
p281
aVThese men are seven inches different in height,
p282
aVbut because of the body types
p283
aVadvantaged in their sports,
p284
aVthey wear the same length pants.
p285
aVSeven inches difference in height,
p286
aVthese men have the same length legs.
