aa(lp326
VStill, even changing technology
p327
aVand the changing gene pool in sports
p328
aVdon't account for all of the changes in performance.
p329
aVAthletes have a different mindset than they once did.
p330
aVHave you ever seen in a movie when someone gets
p331
aVan electrical shock
p332
aVand they're thrown across a room?
p333
aVThere's no explosion there.
p334
aVWhat's happening when that happens is that
p335
aVthe electrical impulse is causing
p336
aVall their muscle fibers to twitch at once,
p337
aVand they're throwing themselves across the room.
p338
aVThey're essentially jumping.
p339
aVThat's the power
p340
aVthat's contained in the human body.
p341
aVBut normally we can't access nearly all of it.
p342
aVOur brain acts as a limiter,
p343
aVpreventing us from accessing all of our physical resources,
p344
aVbecause we might hurt ourselves,
p345
aVtearing tendons or ligaments.
p346
aVBut the more we learn about how that limiter functions,
p347
aVthe more we learn how we can push it back
p348
aVjust a bit,
p349
aVin some cases by convincing the brain
p350
aVthat the body won't be in mortal danger
p351
aVby pushing harder.
p352
aVEndurance and ultra-endurance sports
p353
aVserve as a great example.
p354
aVUltra-endurance was once thought to be harmful
p355
aVto human health,
p356
aVbut now we realize
p357
aVthat we have all these traits
p358
aVthat are perfect for ultra-endurance:
p359
aVno body fur and a glut of sweat glands
p360
aVthat keep us cool while running;
p361
aVnarrow waists and long legs compared to our frames;
p362
aVlarge surface area of joints for shock absorption.
p363
aVWe have an arch in our foot that acts like a spring,
p364
aVshort toes that are better for pushing off
p365
aVthan for grasping tree limbs,
p366
aVand when we run,
p367
aVwe can turn our torso and our shoulders
p368
aVlike this while keeping our heads straight.
p369
aVOur primate cousins can't do that.
p370
aVThey have to run like this.
p371
aVAnd we have big old butt muscles
p372
aVthat keep us upright while running.
p373
aVHave you ever looked at an ape's butt?
p374
aVThey have no buns because they don't run upright.
p375
aVAnd as athletes have realized
p376
aVthat we're perfectly suited for ultra-endurance,
p377
aVthey've taken on feats
p378
aVthat would have been unthinkable before,
p379
aVathletes like Spanish endurance racer Kílian Jornet.
